Package com.rb.nonbiz.functional

Class LinearCollaredRBNumericFunctionBuilder<X extends java.lang.Number,​Y extends RBNumeric<? super Y>>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.functional.LinearCollaredRBNumericFunctionBuilder<X,​Y>
All Implemented Interfaces:
RBBuilder<RBNumericFunction<X,​Y>>
public class LinearCollaredRBNumericFunctionBuilder<X extends java.lang.Number,​Y extends RBNumeric<? super Y>>
extends java.lang.Object
implements RBBuilder<RBNumericFunction<X,​Y>>
This lets us build a linear function with a collar on its Y values (min + max) in a slightly more legible fashion.

The function has y-values =

  1. minY for x in (-inf, minX]
  2. minY + [(x - minX) / (maxX - minX)] * (maxY - minY) for x in [minX, maxX]
  3. maxY for x in [maxX, +inf)

In ASCII art: 

                 (maxX, maxY)
                      *----------------
                     /
                    /
                   /
 -----------------*
             (minX, minY)

Note that the names 'minY' and 'maxY' are misleading. minY is the y-value at x = minX (or below) and maxY is the y-value at x = maxX (or above). As such, minY can be less than, equal to, or greater than maxY.

If minY > maxY, the upwardly-slanted line drawn above would slant downwards: 

            (minX, minY)
 ----------------*
                  \
                   \
                    \
                     *----------------
                (maxX, maxY)

There is nothing preventing you from calling the setters out of order, but if you call them in the order they appear then the resulting code will read a bit like an English sentence.
